## MLT Experience

The use case for our Experience Lab comes from IoT industry. We have an engine with 45 sensors, data from which we receive periodically. There is also a state of the engine:

- 0-normal operation
- 1-engine problems

Which we must predict (in our training dataset we already know what state engine is, so we can train our model on it).

Thankfully, there is already a ML model, which predicts the state of the engine. Moreover, InterSystems IRIS automatically validates and retrains the model if prediction quality fail below an adjustable threshold.

The goals of this Experience Lab are

- See how automated AI/ML pipeline works in InterSystems IRIS
- Improve the model


For successful completion of this Experience, it is recommended (but not mandatory) to be familiar with:

- InterSystems IRIS Data Platform
- [Principal Component Analysis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_analysis)
- [Logistic Regression](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logistic_regression)
- Python

## 1. Production

First, let's get familiar with the production. Open [production management page](/csp/python/EnsPortal.ProductionConfig.zen).

Login: Admin

Password: SYS

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

On this page you will see the main components of the AI/ML production:

- `py.ens.Operation` – executes Python code and sends back the results.
- `ml.engine.TrainProcess` – trains new prediction model.
- `ml.engine.PredictService` – a service that receives information from engine sensors and sends it to ml.engine.PredictProcess to predict engine state. At the moment it is disabled (grey) and does not transfer data.
- `ml.engine.PredictProcess` - uses ML model to predict engine state.
- `ml.engine.CheckService` – regularly checks the accuracy of ML model. If the prediction error rate is above the threshold, the service sends a request to the `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to update the model.
- `ml.engine.InitService` – sends a request to the `ml.engine.TrainProcess` to train the initial model at production start.

## 2. Explore ml.engine.TrainProcess

This is the core process of this Experience. It trains predictive model from supplied data. Open `ml.engine.TrainProcess`. To do this, first click LMB on it in the process list, and then click the magnifying glass in the settings.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

It would open Process Editor page:

![](data:image/*;base64,)

This page shows the individual activities of composing the Training Process.

To view activity on the diagram, select it and click the magnifying glass below the annotation.

![](data:image/*;base64,)

All the activities beginning with the word Wait are used to get results from asynchronous calls, you can ignore them.

Following activities compose the process:

- Import - load Python libraries
- Load Data - load the data for model trainig
- Extract Y - split the data into X - the independent variables and Y - the dependent variable we are predicting
- PCA - The [principal components](https://towardsdatascience.com/a-step-by-step-explanation-of-principal-component-analysis-b836fb9c97e2) calculation for X
- CV - [cross-validation](https://machinelearningmastery.com/k-fold-cross-validation/) of potential models
- Fit - [pipeline](https://www.kaggle.com/baghern/a-deep-dive-into-sklearn-pipelines) creation and training

Annotations contain a more detailed description of activities and an explanation of their behaviors, besides the python code

Questions:

- What does the process receive as a request message?
- What settings are available for configuration?

## 3. Explore ml.engine.CheckService

This service regularly verifies the accuracy of the ML model. The service compares new predictions to the true engine state (which we would eventually discover) and calculates the percentage of errors (by comparing the last thousand of predictions to the true data). If the error rate is above the threshold (an adjustable setting), Check Service sends a request to the ml.engine.TrainProcess to retrain the model.

Return to the production configuration page and click on the `ml.engine.CheckService`.

Then click Log. Results of model validation displayed here.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

On the screenshot, you can see that at the begining there's no predictions to validate (as `PredictService` is disabled).

## 4. Start ml.engine.PredictService

Return to the product configuration page and double click on the ml.engine.PredictService.

You will be prompted to enable the service.

Service status indicator should be green.

Select Predict Service, and in the right menu, select Messages. There click on the `Go to Message Viewer` link:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Or open [MessageViewer](/csp/python/EnsPortal.MessageViewer.zen?SOURCEORTARGET=ml.engine.PredictService).

In the Message Viewer, we can look at the messages generated by the service, select any message and click on the session link:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In the Visual Trace window, which displays information about the interaction of product elements, we can see something like this:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

PredictService sends the new record id to the PredictProcess to predict the condition of engine [1].

PredictProcess causes Python Operation to call trained ML model to predict engine state [2-11]. Python Operation eventually [11] returns the predicted state of the engine, which PredictProcess returns to PredictService in [12].

You can open PredictProcess similarly to TrainingProcess from product configuration page for more details on how prediction works or check Visual Trace for details.

## 6. Improving the model

As you can see, our model does not work very well – it is retrained frequently and error percentage is quite high.

Let us improve this model. To do this, open TrainProcess.

In `CV` activity we are gradually expanding a number of principal components used and the fill mse variable with the deviation of the logistic regression model built on current subset of principal components:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

The output from this step is saved in [DeepSee](/dsw/index.html#!/d/MSE.dashboard?ns=PYTHON).

However, this information remains unused anywhere else.

For example, based on `mse` variable we can build dependency graph for logistic regression model accuracy (y axis, less is better), depending on the number of used principal components (x axis) for the data set:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

From the graph, it follows that for the best model we need to use not all principal components but their optimal amount (which can vary).

Open the Fit activity

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

In it we are creating a [Pipeline](https://www.kaggle.com/baghern/a-deep-dive-into-sklearn-pipelines). Replace the line
```
pca= PCA()
```
With:
```
pca = PCA(n_components = 1 + mse.index(min(mse[1:])))
```


After that in the final model the pipeline will use not all principal components but their optimum subset.

Make the necessary edits in the process, and then click &quot;Compile&quot;.

After compilation open the production configuration page, and then click twice on the ml.engine.TrainProcess to load the new version of the process. In the dialog that appears, choose &quot;Restart&quot;.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)
